		<header>
			
			<h1>Central Africa: Agricultural trade policy debates and developments</h1>

						<div class="pdf-file">
				<a href="/en/layout/set/print/content/download/12156/497062/file/1fd9777d21dea19902dadd3d151af961.pdf">Download <img src="/extension/agritrade/design/agritrade/images/pdf.gif" alt=""/></a>
			</div>
			
			<h4>
									</h4>

						<h2>Executive brief: Update, July 2011</h2>
					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p><b>About this update</b></p><p>This brief was updated in July 2011. The original executive brief was published in January 2009 and is available on request from agritrade-mail@cta.int</p><p>Other publications in this series and additional resources on ACP—EU agriculture and fisheries trade issues can be found online at http://agritrade.cta.int/</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<a name="eztoc497052_1" id="eztoc497052_1"></a><h2><b>1. Introduction and overview </b></h2><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>1.1 Agricultural production</b></p><p>Within the Central African region, Cameroon and the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) play a major role in agricultural production, each contributing 36% to regional agricultural GDP. In terms of farming systems, agriculture is dominated by small-scale producers, except in Cameroon and Republic of Congo, where large-scale commercial farms play a major role.</p><p>Regarding other aspects of agriculture – such as levels of production, type and variety of products, production systems, self-sufficiency and nutrition, and contribution of the sector to GDP – the countries in the region are heterogeneous. There are however common features, the chief one being that agricultural production is generally insufficient both in terms of volume and variety to meet consumer needs. While two countries are almost or partly self-sufficient, the rest of the countries in the region depend heavily on imports to meet consumer needs. The issue of access to food can take on profound political significance at times of rising food prices and food scarcity, and these considerations have an important bearing on policy actions. In 2010, the International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) published its review of developments in Economic Community of Central African States (ECCAS) countries since 1990. This review, in its hunger index, showed only limited progress in reducing hunger in these countries.</p><p>Regarding type of production, ‘the region can be split in two: the north produces mainly cereals, and south is dominated by crops such as coffee, cocoa, roots and tuber.’</p><p><b>Cameroon:</b> in a better situation than the rest of the region as regards self-sufficiency. Although there are variations between districts, Cameroon has fewer undernourished people (23%) than the regional average (53%). The main agricultural products in value terms are plantains (12% of national agricultural production), cattle meat (7%) and cassava (6%). Cameroon also produces cereals, vegetables and cash crops such as cocoa, bananas, coffee, cotton and sugar. Progress in agricultural production has been vigorous and varied since 1999.</p><p><b>Congo, Rep. of:</b> in a similar situation to Cameroon, with only 15% of the population undernourished. However Congo depends heavily on food imports and ‘apart from cassava and plantains, basic foodstuffs show a huge shortfall (only 30% self-sufficiency for meat, 3% for rice, 46% for eggs, 40% for oil).’ Production is concentrated on tubers and livestock, with cassava contributing 30% of agricultural value-added and game meat 19%. Congo also produces bananas, plantains and sugar.</p><p><b>Gabon:</b> the country has a weakly developed agricultural sector and a high dependence on imports (60% of its needs), although only 5% of its population are undernourished. Main crops produced are plantains (27% of the value of agricultural production), game meat (17%) and sweet potato (11%). Cash crops such as rubber, sugar and bananas are also produced, while cocoa and coffee production have declined dramatically since the 1970s.</p><p><b>São Tomé and Principe</b> and <b>Equatorial Guinea:</b> data is lacking on nutrition and self-sufficiency rates.<b> </b>In<b> São Tomé and Principe</b>, the main agricultural crops are: bananas (26%), taro (15%), coconuts (14%) and cocoa (9%). <b>Equatorial Guinea </b>produces cash crops such as coffee (13% of agricultural production value), bananas (10%) and cocoa beans (6%) on a commercial basis, and has a subsistence agricultural sector focused on production of plantain (25%), sweet potato (13%), cassava (12%) and other roots and tubers (10%). In both countries agricultural production insufficient to cover food needs, with a high food import dependency.</p><p>The rest of the countries in the region have insufficient agricultural production to meet the needs of their populations and major problems of undernourishment, which affects between 37 and 69% of the population.</p><p><b>Chad: </b>produces mainly<b> </b>livestock products (cattle meat is 18% of its agricultural production in value terms), groundnuts (15%), cereals (24%, made up of millet, sorghum, cereals, rice and maize) and cotton (5%). Despite these high levels of cereals production, Chad suffers from chronic cereals shortfalls.</p><p><b>Central African Republic (CAR): </b>subsistence agriculture dominates (98% of agricultural value-added in 2005). Cattle meat and groundnuts are the main products (27% and 10% of agricultural value-added). Tubers such as sweet potato and cassava are also produced, but production does not cover the population’s needs. There are shortfalls in cereals, sugar and fats production, with wide regional disparities in availability. Over three decades, the production of cash crops such as coffee and cotton has decreased, with rates of growth in production of crops and animals below the rate of population increase.</p><p><b>DRC:</b> the food availability situation is acute, with 69% of the population undernourished). In recent decades, in the face of high population growth, the animal population and food production have decreased or stagnated and food insecurity has worsened. The main agricultural products are cassava (39% in value of agricultural production), plantains, groundnuts and cereals (rice and maize). Production of cash crops such as tobacco, palm oil, sugar cane and coffee has decreased dramatically in recent decades.</p><p><i>&nbsp;</i></p><p><b>1.2 Agricultural trade</b></p><p>Central Africa is poorly integrated economically, with very low regional trade flows. This is despite the existence of two regional integration processes: the CEMAC (Communauté économique et monétaire d’Afrique centrale – Economic and Monetary Community of Central Africa) and the ECCAS (Communauté économique des États d’Afrique centrale, CEEAC). In CEMAC, despite the existence of a customs union, some studies have estimated that regional trade accounted for between only 2 and 6% of total trade in the early 2000s. According to CEMAC Commission data for 2005, intra-CEMAC trade amounts to less than 150 billion CFA francs (some US$326 million) and focuses primary on oil products.</p><p>The United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (UNECA) has estimated intra-ECCAS trade at between 1.3 and 3.8% of total ECCAS imports during the period 2001–2005, while a 2007 assessment put the figure at 1.4 % of total ECCAS imports (US$369 million). Intra-regional trade is thus of relatively minor significance.</p><p>Regionally traded agricultural and food products include: refined sugar; soup preparations; vegetable oils; beers and tobacco products. Cereals, fruits and vegetables are on the whole not part of official intra-regional trade flows.</p><p>The main actor in CEMAC regional trade is Cameroon, which is involved in around 60% of all intra-regional trade. This trade however represents only 5% of Cameroon’s total external trade. Cameroon is the only net agricultural exporter, while all other countries in CEMAC are net importers. Cameroon supplies its neighbouring countries mainly with meat products and fruits and vegetables.</p><p>Central African countries trade mainly with the EU (for 40% of their imports and 82% of their exports). Other major sources of imports include Brazil, Thailand and China, while the region’s other main export markets are China (3.63%) and the USA (2.35%).</p><p>The main exported agricultural product is cocoa, which brings in 45.8% of export earnings. Other major export products include bananas and other edible fruits and nuts (26.8%), cotton (8.45%), coffee (8.42%) and tobacco (2.4%).</p><p>Cameroon dominates regional exports, with 85% of the value of regional agricultural exports. Cameroon’s main export products are: cocoa (61%); bananas (25%); coffee and cotton (5% each). DRC (tobacco and coffee), Chad (cotton) and Congo (coffee, oil seed, and tobacco) export each between 3 and 5 % of the region’s agricultural exports.</p><p>The export position of a number of Central African countries has deteriorated since the 1970s. The DRC was formerly a major producer of palm oil and cotton (it was the second largest producer of palm oil and the leading African producer of cotton), but is now a net importer. Coffee, rubber, cocoa and tea have also declined. Similarly, in Gabon production of coffee and cocoa has declined 90% compared to the 1970s level. In Chad, meanwhile, while cotton is still the second most important export, the relative importance of Chad in cotton production in the franc zone has changed dramatically, from being the leading producer to being the smallest. Chad’s leading non-petroleum export remains livestock exports to neighbouring countries such as Nigeria and Cameroon.</p><p>In terms of imports the region shows a shortfall in production of cereals and milled cereal products, meat products, beverages, fats and oils and dairy products. As a consequence, the main imported agricultural products include cereals (16% of import value), meat products (12%), milled cereal products (9%), beverages (8%), fats and oil (7%) and dairy and animal products (7%). The main importers include DRC, Cameroon, Congo and Gabon, which account for between 15% and 27% of regional agricultural imports.</p><p><b>1.3 Situating agricultural trade policy</b></p><p>Agriculture and agricultural trade policy in Central African countries remain a national responsibility. Central African countries have different interests in the agricultural sector, depending on the importance of mineral resources in some of the countries. In terms of the use of agricultural trade policy tools, there is considerable divergence among member states of the EU–Central African Economic Partnership Agreement (EPA) configuration.</p><p><b>Cameroon: </b>the government imposes<b> </b>various requirements on coffee and cocoa exports, including various fees, supervision of marketing by national marketing boards and the management of industry funds to stabilise the sector and promote value-added processing. In addition, export taxes are imposed as a revenue-generating tool.</p><p><b>Chad: </b>uses export tax for live cattle and dried fish, as well as a variety of other products (World Trade Organisation Trade Policy Review 2007). Since 2003, Chad has also prohibited exports of heifers and calves to preserve the livestock population. Local administrative authorities may also restrict cereal exports at any time, in the event of shortages. Since 2006, sugar has to be imported by companies affiliated to the Chad Sugar Company.</p><p><b>CAR:</b> exports taxes, restrictions on imports and import licensing arrangements are all used, with quantitative import restrictions used for sugar and coffee (WTO Trade Policy Review 2007).</p><p><b>Congo:</b> uses quantitative restrictions and imports licensing arrangements in order to protect its industries and to control the supply and prices of goods, particularly sugar and wheat (WTO Trade Policy Review 2006).</p><p><b>Gabon: </b>prohibits imports of sugar from countries outside CEMAC (WTO Trade Policy Review 2006).</p><p><b>DRC:</b> operates a four-band tariff (0%, 5%, 10% and 20%), with average applied agricultural tariffs of 12.8% and imports subject to import licences. This measure is nominally used for statistical purposes. Imports of sugar are subject to quantitative restrictions. Export taxes are also levied on green coffee (WTO Trade Policy Review 2011).</p><p><b>São Tomé and Principe:</b> the tariff regime has 3 bands: 5% for basic goods, 20% for luxury goods, and 10% for all other imports (mostly capital equipment items). According to a World Bank report, São Tomé and Principe has eliminated all non-tariff barriers and export taxes.</p><p>Following the 2008 food price crisis, various new measures were set in place across the region, ranging from consumption support measures, through the lowering of import taxes and domestic tax rates on agricultural products, to export restrictions and outright bans.</p><p>However efforts are under way to harmonise national policies, including at the levels of CEMAC and ECCAS. In addition, some Central African governments have signed Comprehensive African Agricultural Development Programme (CAADP) compacts – an initiative under New Partnership for Africa’s Development (NEPAD) which aims to stimulate growth in agricultural by 6% per annum, through the expansion of government expenditures in support of agricultural development to 10% of the national budget.</p><p>CEMAC member states and its Executive Secretariat have been working on a common agricultural strategy since 1996. This process was completed in 2003, with the formal adoption of an agricultural strategy regulation. Within this strategy a specific programme is dedicated to food security (PRSA, the Programme régional de sécurité alimentaire) which was developed FAO support. Given the rich biodiversity of the region, enhancing intra-regional trade within CEMAC could play a strong role in addressing underlying food security concerns. The governments of CEMAC remain committed to meeting Millennium Development Goal objectives, most importantly in regard to the fight against hunger. Across the region, considerable importance is attached to strengthening agro-industries, which is seen as a means of promoting economic and trade diversification. This perspective has an influence on the use of agricultural trade policy tools and the approach to agricultural trade negotiations.</p><p>ECCAS also has a similar process currently under way to develop a regional agricultural policy. This also includes a PRSA regional food security programme, which has been developed with assistance from the African Development Bank. In response to the 2008 food price crisis, ECCAS created the FSRDA fund (Fonds spécial régional de développement agricole – Special Regional Agricultural Development Fund) to promote food security. However by the beginning of 2011 only four member states had contributed to the fund.</p><p>The objectives of the PSRA regional food security programmes included the coordination and harmonisation of food security and agricultural policies, the promotion of regional trade in agricultural products and the improvement of competitiveness on the world market.</p><p>According to the UNECA report, the implementation of the PRSAs has been delayed by a lack of funding. Although some projects have been implemented, major programmes related to the development of agricultural infrastructure, production and marketing of high yield seeds, value-added processing and the facilitation of intra-regional trade remain pending.</p><p>According to the UNECA stock-taking report, these two regional initiatives should merge and include the following components:</p>
<ul>

<li>the national agricultural strategies;</li>

<li>the PRSA food security regional programme;</li>

<li>the thematic pillars of CAADP;</li>

<li>regional initiatives which emerged after the 2008 food price crisis (including the FSRDA fund).</li>

</ul>
<p>Regarding the national agricultural strategies, according to the UNECA, 6 out of the 10 ECCAS member states have ratified their strategies, with the remaining four (Angola, Equatorial Guinea, São Tomé and Principe, and DRC) expected to complete the process in 2011.</p><a name="eztoc497052_2" id="eztoc497052_2"></a><h2><b>2. Regional agricultural trade policy developments</b></h2><p><b>2.1 Agriculture in the national context</b></p><p>In the CAR and DRC, agriculture accounts for 54% and 45% of GDP respectively. In Cameroon, Chad and São Tomé and Principe, agriculture contributes between 12 and 19% of GDP, while in Congo, Gabon and Equatorial Guinea agriculture is of minor importance, accounting for less than 5% of GDP. Table 1 sets out a number of statistics showing the importance of agriculture within the countries of the region.</p><p>In terms of employment, a distinction can be made between two types of country.</p>
<ul>

<li>Category 1: countries with a predominantly rural population (60–72%), with more than 20% of the active population working in agriculture. This is the case for the non oil-producing countries of CAR and DRC, as well as Chad and Equatorial Guinea. </li>

<li>Category 2: countries where agriculture is less important, since the population lives mainly in urban areas (up to 62%) and agriculture provides jobs for only between 13 and 19% of the active population.</li>

</ul>
<p>Despite these differences, it seems there is a policy consensus on the importance of getting to grips with the region-wide challenge of food insecurity. The need for a strong agricultural policy is recognised by all Central African states, but despite nominal policy commitments, progress has been very slow.</p><p><b>Table 1: Importance of agriculture in Central African countries</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="540">
