<p>Source: International Trade Centre, TradeMap</p><p>Note: * nes = not elsewhere specified</p><p>In the DRC, the principal food imports are wheat (grain and flour), refined sugar, maize, milk and poultry meat. Moreover, despite the potential for DRC to be self-sufficient and to provide the region with maize, 20% of maize requirements are imported, and 100% of wheat requirements are covered by imports. Poultry imports have increased markedly since 1999, rising from 22,000 to 51,000 tonnes in 2007.</p><p>In Chad, the main import is wheat flour. Despite its growing potential for sugar, Chad imports 60% of its requirements. Chad and CAR record a low proportion of imports from the region (with 5% and 1% each), despite their shortfalls in food production.</p><p>Regional integration efforts are complicated by the DRC’s multiple membership of regional bodies including: ECCAS, the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), the Southern African Development Community (SADC), and the Economic Community of the Great Lakes Countries (which is not operational). The DRC’s weak effective participation in these bodies however does not make this an insurmountable problem.</p><p>2.2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Agriculture and agricultural trade policy in CEMAC</p><p>There are six countries in CEMAC: Gabon, Cameroon, Congo, Equatorial Guinea, Chad, CAR. The main aim of CEMAC is to promote the establishment of a common market based on free movement of persons, capital and services. There is also a commitment to the coordination of national policies to ensure a stable economic and business environment and the harmonisation of sector policy regulations, most notably in the agriculture, livestock and fisheries sectors.</p><p>A CEMAC free-trade area (FTA) has nominally been in force since 1998. CEMAC moved towards a custom union between 1994 and 2000, with the establishment of a four-band common external tariff (CET):</p>
<ul>

<li>Category I for vital goods – 5%;</li>

<li>Category II for raw materials and equipment goods – 10%;</li>

<li>Category III for intermediary goods – 20%;</li>

<li>Category IV for goods of usual consumption – 30%. </li>

</ul>
<p>However agricultural products do not fit easily into this four-tier categorisation. Within CEMAC, the average of applied agricultural tariffs amounts to between 21.9 and 25.1%. The main imported agricultural products are subject to the highest tariff rates, 20% and 30%, except wheat for which a 10% rate is applied. Table 3 sets out a number of products alongside the CET that applies to them.</p><p><b>Table 3: Level of common external tariff for agricultural products</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="540">
