<a href="http://www.izf.net/upload/TEC/afrique%20centrale/" target="_self">http://www.izf.net/upload/TEC/afrique%20centrale/</a></p><p>In addition to tariff protection, CEMAC countries continue to use various agricultural trade policy tools, including import licensing arrangements, quantitative restrictions on imports and exports and export taxes.</p><p>According to the WTO TPR of 2007, Cameroon imposes import restrictions on meat products, notably poultry meat. In 2006, the Citizens' Association for the Defence of Collective Interests (Association des citoyens pour la défense des interêts collectifs – ACDIC) conducted a campaign to restrict imports of frozen chickens from Europe and Latin America, with a view to protecting and promoting local poultry production. Measures taken by the government in response to this campaign include a substantial reduction in the number of chicken import permits issued, a limit on the volume of imports, the establishment of health control posts at the border where transit taxes are paid (foreign animals are also subject to specific duties) and temporary price control measures. Similar measures are also applied to imports of cattle and small livestock.</p><p>In terms of intra-CEMAC trade, according to a UNECA stock-taking report in 2009,&nbsp;‘the generalised preferential tariff applies on the whole to every origin product and product traded with a CEMAC circulation certificate’, but derogations and safeguard clauses for countries in conflicts have been granted (to Congo, 2000–2002, and to CAR, 2004–2007). This extends to the use of import restrictions on intra-CEMAC trade. Table 4 sets out how the countries of the region use and apply different trade policy instruments.</p><p><b>Table 4: Trade policy instruments in force in the CEMAC region</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
