<p>Source: WTO Trade Policy Reviews</p><p>According to the UNECA, two problems have impeded the consolidation of a harmonised trade policy:</p>
<ul>

<li>the absence of a common policy on export taxes; </li>

<li>the national establishment of exceptions to the CET. </li>

</ul>
<p>This has affected agricultural products such as: vegetable oil, maize, salt, refined sugars and dairy products, and has led to an erosion of the common external tariff. This is attributed to the absence of an effective regional body for negotiating modifications to the CET and enforcing compliance.</p><p>Overall, analysis to date suggests that regional integration in CEMAC has not had a significant impact on the intra-regional trade amongst CEMAC members. Critical constraints on intra-regional trade are the poor transport infrastructure in the region and a lack of complementarity in production structures.</p><p><b>2.3 Agriculture and agricultural trade policy in ECCAS</b></p><p>The ECCAS established in 1983 is composed of 10 member states: Cameroon, Central African Republic, Chad, Republic of Congo, Democratic Republic of Congo, Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, São Tomé and Principe, as well as Angola and Burundi. The objective of ECCAS is to promote and strengthen cooperation and economic development, including in agriculture.</p><p>The ECCAS member countries have adopted a tariff reduction scheme for intra‑Community trade, known as the ECCAS Preferential Tariff, which should in principle have come into effect between 2004 and 2007. In 2007 it had been proposed that the ECCAS CET should include three tariff bands (at 5, 10 and 20%). However, according to the WTO, ‘tariff reduction has not actually been implemented’.</p><p>There would appear to be a need in the coming period to harmonise the ECCAS and CEMAC common external tariff (CET). This however could prove to be a difficult exercise, given that Burundi is already a part of the East African Community Customs Union, while Angola is nominally a part of the SADC customs union process and part of the SADC EPA configuration.</p><a name="eztoc497052_3" id="eztoc497052_3"></a><h2><b>3. Wider trade negotiations and developments</b></h2><p><b>3.1 The EPA negotiations</b></p><p>The EU’s EPA negotiations with the Central African configuration of countries began in 2003. However it was not possible to conclude a regional agreement before 2008. As a consequence, in order to maintain its existing duty-free, quota-free access, Cameroon initialled a bilateral interim EPA (IEPA) with the EU at the end of 2007, and this was formally signed on 15 January 2009.</p><p>Gabon and Congo, the two non-least developed countries (LDCs) left in the region, have traded under standard GSP preferences (Generalised System of [tariff] Preferences) since 2008. The European Commission (EC) proposals to revise the EU GSP would see Gabon graduated out of the GSP scheme (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/Agriculture/Topics/Market-access/Commission-unveils-proposal-for-new-GSP" target="_self">Commission unveils proposal for new GSP</a>’, June 2011), The LDCs in the region continue to benefit from the ‘Everything But Arms’ (EBA) initiative.</p><p>Due to institutional constraints on the Central African side, the EPA negotiations were halted in February 2009 and only resumed in December 2010, with a stock-taking meeting in Douala, Cameroon. This meeting was followed by two other meetings in February and April 2011 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/EPAs/Central-African-EPA-negotiations-relaunched" target="_self">Central African EPA negotiations relaunched</a>’, April 2011), at which issues related to market access, rules of origin, and accompanying measures were discussed. Because of the disparities in the institutional framework between the EC on the one hand and Central Africa on the other, Central African negotiators have called for the postponement of the services negotiations. According to the European Centre for Development Policy Management (ECDPM), Equatorial Guinea has signified its intention not to join the EPA before 2020.</p><p>The negotiations for a regional EPA are ongoing, but they continue to be frustrated by the differences of opinions between the two parties mainly concerning the provisions on the financing of support measures and Central Africa’s market access offer. Given the financial difficulties in the EU, negotiations around accompanying measures are likely to continue to prove difficult.</p><p>After the rejection of Central Africa’s initial market access offer (elimination of tariffs on 60% of imports over 25 years), a new offer was tabled in July 2008 (71% over 20 years). This still excluded some 1,205 products, representing 24.5% of the tariff lines. During the July 2008 meeting, ‘the EU repeated that 80% of products should be liberalised over 15 years’. No agreement was reached. In the 2011 meetings, the EC and Central African negotiators have been exploring the possibility of abandoning a generalised tariff liberalisation approach to negotiations in favour of tariff-line by tariff-line discussions, which could allow the two parties to reach a favourable outcome.</p><p>Beyond these questions, the extensive use of a range of trade policy tools in the region is likely to give rise to complications in the EPA process. Under the Cameroon–EU IEPA, measures involving quantitative restrictions (such as import bans, quotas and licences) are formally prohibited, even for the purpose of protecting new industries or for reasons of food security. It is unclear whether this clause will be integrated into any Central African–EU regional EPA, although this is clearly the desire of the EC. According to the WTO Trade Policy Review, as Central African countries apply measures involving quantitative restrictions on imports in the agricultural sector for reasons of food security or to protect new sectors or industries, any prohibition of such measures could cause a problem.</p><p>As regards export taxes, no compromise has yet been reached. The Cameroon–EU IEPA allows the maintenance of export taxes, if the taxes in question were in place before the agreement. It only authorises the introduction of new export taxes ‘for environmental protection purposes or to maintain monetary stability, after consultation with the EC’.</p><p>If the Central African countries want to be able to continue to use this type of instrument, it will be important to ensure that the regional agreement includes a certain degree of flexibility regarding their use, in particular for reasons of food security or to protect new industries.</p><p>In February 2011, a commitment was made to completing the negotiations by the end of 2011. However, it is unclear on what basis the negotiations could be concluded by the end of 2011.</p><p><b>3.2 Other trade negotiations</b></p><p>With the exception of the DRC’s periodic engagement with the COMESA and SADC FTA negotiations, Central African governments are not involved in any trade negotiations that have been notified to the WTO.</p><p><i>&nbsp;</i></p><a name="eztoc497052_4" id="eztoc497052_4"></a><h2><b>4. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Current agricultural trade policy debates and issues</b></h2><p><b>4.1 Consolidating and operationalising agricultural and agricultural trade policies</b></p><p>While nominally agricultural and agricultural trade policy harmonisation strategies are in place, there remain problems of inter-institutional competition, with a lack of clarity on which institution should lead on which aspects of regional agricultural and agricultural trade policy formulation. There is an urgent need to address this issue in order to get to grips with effectively operationalising existing strategies through national actions, coordinated within a common regional framework. This could help to overcome the lack of progress to date, which has commonly been attributed to a lack of funding for regional cooperation on agricultural issues.</p><p>Promotion of the adoption of CAADP strategic commitments offers one avenue for operationalising existing policy commitments. However, so far only two governments in the region have adopted CAADP compacts (DRC and Central African Republic – on 17 March 2010 and 15 April 2011 respectively). To date none of the Central African countries have reached the 10% target for budget allocations to the agricultural sector. Even in Cameroon, the region’s most advanced agricultural producer, only about 2.34% of Cameroon’s national budget is allocated to agricultural and rural development activities. In terms of the agricultural growth objectives, only Congo has succeeded in attaining an agricultural production growth rate of 6%.</p><p>There is thus a considerable challenge ahead for the region in operationalising the nominal commitment to prioritising agricultural production and promoting a coordinated regional approach to agricultural sector development.</p><p><b>4.2 Establishing an effective common external tariff</b></p><p>A major issue in the CEMAC context is the elimination of anomalies in the application of the common external tariff arising from derogations, the application of safeguard measures and the introduction of special measures in response to the 2008 food price surge. This requires the establishment of effective mechanisms for the common review of common tariffs. However, it should be noted that this is not necessarily posing any major economic challenges at the moment, given the limited volume of intra-regional trade.</p><p>A related challenge is the establishment of a process for the gradual convergence of the national tariff policies of São Tomé and Principe and the Democratic Republic of the Congo with that of the CEMAC common external tariff.</p><p>It is far from clear how this might to be achieved in 2011 in such as way as to enable the region to table a common tariff elimination offer to the EC. This could give rise to a regional agreement consisting of several separate national tariff elimination offers. This is not going to pose a problem for EU exporters of food and agricultural products, who would welcome any process of tariff elimination (no matter how fragmented), and would certainly welcome the dismantling of non-tariff barriers to trade in food and agricultural products. However, it could store up problems for any future efforts to consolidate an effective common external tariff in the CEMAC and wider Central African region.</p><p><b>4.3 Developing regional agricultural trade</b></p><p>Despite a nominal agreement on the need for a strong agricultural policy, it is unclear to what extent a consensus exists in the region on the nature of the agricultural and associated agricultural trade policy that is appropriate for the Central African region. The interests of Central African governments in agricultural production vary considerably, and it is unclear where the common ground exists for the elaboration of a common policy on trade in food and agricultural products.</p><p>An initial starting point might be the establishment of greater transparency on the current agricultural trade policy tools in use, and the national policy perspectives on the future use of such tools in different agricultural sectors, and how the tools might be prioritised for development in the region. This could allow scope for the elaboration of sector-by-sector approaches to agricultural and agricultural trade policy harmonisation, based on the capacities for production and trade which exist within the region and the development aspirations of different sector organisations in the region.</p><p><b>Main sources</b></p><p>1. UNECA, ‘Etat d'avancement du processus d'intégration en Afrique Centrale: Prospectus 2009’, 2009</p><p>
<a href="http://www.uneca.org/ac/Publications/Prospectus%202009.pdf" target="_self">http://www.uneca.org/ac/Publications/Prospectus%202009.pdf</a></p><p>2. UNECA, ‘Etat d’avancement du processus d’intégration régionale en Afrique centrale. Rapport 2010’, 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.uneca.org/ac/CIE2010/Documents/CE%202010%20Rapport%20Integration%20Regionale.pdf" target="_self">http://www.uneca.org/ac/CIE2010/Documents/CE%202010%20Rapport%20Integrat...</a></p><p>3. CIRAD and GRET, ‘Impact sur l’agriculture de la CEMAC et Sao Tomé et Principe d’un Accord de partenariat économique avec l’Union européenne’, by E. Douya, B. Hermelin and V. Ribier, <i>Projet 095 – CEMAC #3</i>,<i> </i>March 2006</p><p>
<a href="http://www.inter-reseaux.org/IMG/pdf/cemac_etude_impact_ape_sur_agriculture.pdf" target="_self">http://www.inter-reseaux.org/IMG/pdf/cemac_etude_impact_ape_sur_agricult...</a></p><p>4. African Development Bank Group, ‘CEEAC - Appui au programme régional pour la sécurité alimentaire’, 2011</p><p>
